<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="18">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Sphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sphecodes barbatus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="18">Sphecodes barbatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. majalis" pageId="5" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="majalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="18">S. majalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The two species are easily separable in the female, but males are difficult. The female 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. barbatus" pageId="5" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="barbatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="18">S. barbatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. majalis" pageId="5" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="majalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="18">S. majalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by denser, distinctly plumose pubescence on paraocular areas and clypeus (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 2–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 2 - 7. Head, females, frontal view. 2 Sphecodes majalis Perez 3 S. scabricollis Wesmael 4 S. barbatus Bluethgen 5 S. atlanticus Warncke 6 S. rubripes Spinola 7 S. albilabris (Fabricius). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.872.35361.figures2-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/327081" pageId="5" pageNumber="18">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) (sparser, weakly plumose or simple pubescence in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. majalis" pageId="5" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="majalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="18">S. majalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 2–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 2 - 7. Head, females, frontal view. 2 Sphecodes majalis Perez 3 S. scabricollis Wesmael 4 S. barbatus Bluethgen 5 S. atlanticus Warncke 6 S. rubripes Spinola 7 S. albilabris (Fabricius). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.872.35361.figures2-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/327081" pageId="5" pageNumber="18">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) and by a distinctly (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 16–19" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 16 - 19. T 1 (16, 17), metasoma (18, 19), females, dorsal view. 16 Sphecodes majalis Perez 17 S. barbatus Bluethgen 18 S. scabricollis Wesmael 19 S. atlanticus Warncke. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.872.35361.figures16-19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/327084" pageId="5" pageNumber="18">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) punctate T1 (sparse and tiny punctures in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. majalis" pageId="5" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="majalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="18">S. majalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 16–19" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 16 - 19. T 1 (16, 17), metasoma (18, 19), females, dorsal view. 16 Sphecodes majalis Perez 17 S. barbatus Bluethgen 18 S. scabricollis Wesmael 19 S. atlanticus Warncke. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.872.35361.figures16-19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/327084" pageId="5" pageNumber="18">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
